## The East-West Rule

This is the governing principle of all pear diamond eternity and anniversary bands, and it is never explained in band listings — only implied by the design photos.

Pear diamonds in bands are always set horizontally across the band width, with the stone's long axis running perpendicular to the band's circumference (east-west). A vertically oriented pear stone in a band — long axis running along the circumference — would constantly rotate under finger pressure. The asymmetric weight distribution of a pear (heavier at the belly than at the tip) pulls the stone off-center the moment any lateral force is applied. Without rotation resistance, every pear stone in the band would shift independently within hours of wear.

East-west orientation solves this because the stone's center of gravity sits at the midpoint of the band width. Weight is distributed evenly from the shank's inner edge to its outer edge, so there is no directional pull. The stone stays put.

This is why every pear diamond band on the market — at Blue Nile and elsewhere — uses east-west orientation. It is not a style choice. It is a functional requirement. When you see a pear diamond band, you are seeing the East-West Rule applied to every stone.

The visual consequence: the pear stones in an anniversary band read as a series of small teardrop shapes turned sideways. This creates a distinctive scalloped visual rhythm along the band that is specific to pear diamonds and recognizable as different from both round and marquise eternity bands.

