## Metal Matching: The Rule That Overrides Everything Else

No advice in this guide matters if you get the metal wrong. Wedding bands and engagement rings on the same finger are in constant contact. Any metal color or karat mismatch will be visible every time you look at your hand.

**Match metal type exactly.** White gold engagement ring requires a white gold band. Yellow gold ring requires a yellow gold band. Rose gold requires rose gold. Two different metal colors on adjacent rings looks like an oversight, not a deliberate choice — unless you have specifically researched mixed-metal stacking, which is a different aesthetic.

**Match karat exactly.** A 14K yellow gold engagement ring worn alongside an 18K yellow gold band will show a visible color difference within months of daily wear. 18K yellow gold is noticeably richer and warmer in color than 14K. This difference is subtle in jewelry store lighting and obvious in direct sunlight.

**Platinum with platinum only.** Never pair platinum with white gold. Platinum is a slightly warmer grey-white; white gold is plated in rhodium and appears bright, cool white. Side by side the difference is stark. Over time, as white gold's rhodium plating wears, the contrast increases further.

| Engagement Ring Metal | Wedding Band Rule |
|---|---|
| 14K Yellow Gold | 14K Yellow Gold only |
| 14K White Gold | 14K White Gold only |
| 14K Rose Gold | 14K Rose Gold only |
| 18K Yellow Gold | 18K Yellow Gold only |
| 18K White Gold | 18K White Gold only |
| Platinum | Platinum only |

One exception: if you are intentionally doing a mixed-metal stacking aesthetic (e.g., yellow gold engagement ring + rose gold band as a deliberate two-tone choice), this works — but it requires that both rings are chosen as a set with the contrast intentional and visible, not accidentally mismatched.

