## Expert Summary

Wedding bands for pear shaped diamonds require one decision before all others: gap problem or no gap problem. The Gap Problem is geometric — a pear diamond's asymmetric belly prevents standard straight bands from sitting flush against the ring shank. Ring enhancers (Crown Diamond Insert at $994, Winged Rollover at $2,190) solve it by design. Standalone bands (Pear+Round at $742, Pear+Round+Pavé at $749) do not.

The East-West Rule governs all pear diamond eternity bands: pear stones are always oriented horizontally across the band because vertical pear stones rotate under finger pressure. Every pear diamond band at Blue Nile follows this convention. The 9-Stone Pear Anniversary Ring at $1,395 is the best pear diamond band in the catalog — verified, discounted, and available in both gold options.

Metal matching overrides aesthetic preference: match karat and metal type exactly to your engagement ring. A 14K/18K mismatch or white gold/platinum mismatch will show visible color difference within months of daily wear. At Blue Nile, all the key band designs are available across 14K, 18K, and platinum, so there is no reason to compromise on karat matching.

## Frequently Asked Questions

### Why won't a regular straight band work next to a pear diamond ring?
The belly curve of the pear diamond's setting protrudes beyond the ring shank. A flat-bottomed straight band cannot follow this curve, leaving a visible gap on the rounded side of the pear. This is a geometric issue, not a sizing issue, and it cannot be fixed by adjusting ring size.

### What is a ring enhancer and how does it work with a pear diamond?
A ring enhancer is a shaped insert designed to nest around the engagement ring's setting. It has a cutout that follows the profile of the solitaire, cradles the setting from both sides, and eliminates the gap between the engagement ring and the wedding band. The Crown Diamond Insert and Winged Rollover at Blue Nile are both ring enhancers specifically shaped for pear diamonds.

### What is the best wedding band for a pear shaped diamond ring?
If your goal is to eliminate the gap: the Crown Diamond Insert in your matching metal (available from $994). If your goal is a standalone band with pear diamonds: the East-West 9-Stone Pear Anniversary Ring at $1,395. If your goal is the lowest price for a pear-featuring band: the Pear and Round Diamond Ring in 14K at $742.

### Why are pear diamonds in wedding bands set east-west?
Pear diamonds set vertically in a band would constantly rotate under finger pressure because the stone's weight is asymmetric — heavier at the belly than at the tip. East-west orientation puts the stone's center of gravity on the band's center line, distributing weight evenly and preventing rotation. This is a functional requirement, not a style choice, which is why every pear diamond band uses east-west setting.

### Should my wedding band match my engagement ring metal exactly?
Yes. Wedding bands and engagement rings are in constant contact on the same finger. Any metal color or karat difference will show as a visible tonal mismatch. 14K and 18K yellow gold look different colors in direct light. Platinum and white gold look different after the rhodium plating on white gold begins to wear. Match both metal type and karat.

### Can I solder my pear engagement ring and wedding band together?
Yes, but understand it is a permanent decision. Soldering fixes the orientation of your pear diamond permanently. If your stone is set point-up and you later prefer point-down, it cannot be changed after soldering without removing and resetting the stone. Confirm your preferred orientation before any soldering work.

### What width wedding band works best with a pear diamond solitaire?
1.5–2.5mm is the most versatile range for most pear diamond solitaires. Narrow bands create minimal visual competition and reduce the visible gap on the belly side. Bands over 3.5mm create proportional issues unless the solitaire has a wide, heavy shank to match. Ring enhancers (which wrap the solitaire rather than sitting beside it) can be wider without the same constraints.

### Is the Crown Diamond Insert or the Winged Rollover the better choice?
For most pear diamond rings, the Crown Insert. It provides complete gap elimination at $994 (30% off) with 1/4 CTW of diamond coverage. The Winged Rollover at $2,190 provides more diamond coverage (5/8 CTW) and a more dramatic winged design — appropriate for prominent pear solitaires over 1.5 CTW where the Crown Insert's diamond coverage would look undersized.

### Can I wear a sapphire wedding band with a pear diamond engagement ring?
Yes. A sapphire and diamond band paired with a pear diamond solitaire creates a color-accent combination. The blue sapphire reads as a deliberate choice rather than a competing diamond. This works best with pear rings in white gold or platinum, where the sapphire's blue color contrasts cleanly with the colorless metal. The Sapphire and Diamond Ring in 14K WG at $798 is the entry point for this combination.

### What is the East-West 9-Stone Pear Diamond Ring?
It is an anniversary or wedding band at Blue Nile featuring nine pear-cut diamonds set horizontally (east-west) across the band in an alternating pattern. Total CTW is 1/2 ct. across both the white and yellow gold versions, currently 25% off at $1,395. It is the definitive pear diamond band — a band where the pear shape is the design, not just an accent.

### Do ring enhancers work with all pear diamond settings?
Most pear diamond settings, yes — but very high cathedral settings may not be compatible with standard enhancers because the enhancer's interior cutout cannot reach far enough up the setting height to nest correctly. For high-set pear solitaires (cathedral settings over 5mm elevation), have a jeweler test the enhancer fit before purchasing. Low-set and bezel pear rings work with ring enhancers without issue.

### What is the pear diamond eternity band option at Blue Nile?
Two options at the statement level: the Mixed Shape Diamond Eternity Ring in Platinum at $10,710 (~~$15,300~~, 30% off) featuring 3.5 CTW of mixed diamond shapes including pear, and the Pear-Cut Half and Half Yellow Diamond Eternity Ring at $11,890 from the Extraordinary Collection with yellow and white pear diamonds alternating across an 18K yellow and white gold band.

### How much should I spend on a wedding band for a pear diamond ring?
The budget answer: 10–20% of your engagement ring's value is a conventional guideline for a wedding band. At Blue Nile's current discount levels (25–30% off most pear wedding band styles), you can access meaningful diamond coverage at $742–$1,395 for a standalone band and $994 for a ring enhancer. Platinum versions of the same designs run 15–25% higher.

